                        <additions>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="SL1r" to="SL1r" scheme="folios"/>
                                <note>Top of page in black ink by a 19th century hand: <quote>Kgl. Bibl. 1734 års Kat. Theol. in 4<hi rend="super">o</hi> no 12</quote>; below by same hand: <quote>Missale</quote>; center page in pencil by a modern hand: <quote>Troligen från Österrike (Stiftet Salzburg? Obs. Den h. Rupert dag och translatio oo? Virgilius 13 okt Cholomannus, festum duplex!). Säkert från Melk. se bl. 261!!</quote>.</note>
                            </p>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="unknown">
                                <p>Medieval binding. Red leather over wooden boards. 3 double raised bands and endbands. Corner pieces and bosses in brass.</p>
                                <p/>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>, stamped in gold: <quote>A 174</quote>.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="260" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="180" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="130" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <decoNote type="tooling">
                                    <p>Blind tooled concentric panels filled with geometrical and vegetative patterns.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                                <condition>Binding heavily damaged. Most of <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/> and <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/> have been replaced by a modern paper over cardboard binding, which is also damaged. Only the <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/> and the parts of the front and back covers closest to the spine are intact. On these parts the leather is heavily worn and repaired.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100208">Austria</placeName>
                                </origPlace>, <origDate notAfter="1500" notBefore="1401">15th century</origDate> The place of origin is based on the inclusion of the saints Rupert, Virgilius and Cholomannus in the calendar and Proper of saints. These saints may point more specifically to <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100278">Salzburg</placeName> or <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100279"> Melk</placeName>, where they were especially venerated.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Early provenance unknown. According to the old library catalogues, the missal has belonged to the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">National Library</orgName> since the 17th century. The note on <locus from="SL1r" to="SL1r" scheme="folios"/> refers to the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e), where it is listed as <quote>Theol in 4<hi rend="super">o</hi> no 12</quote>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
                    <msPart>
